{{Infobox book| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Women Who Run with the Wolves: Myths and Stories of the Wild Woman Archetype | image = Women Who Run with the Wolves.jpg | caption = | author = [[Clarissa Pinkola Estés]] | country = [[United States]] | language = English | subject = | publisher = [[Ballantine Books]] | release_date = 1992 | media_type = Print | pages = 520 | isbn = 0-345-37744-3 | dewey = | congress = | oclc = |preceded_by = |followed_by = }} '''''Women Who Run with the Wolves: Myths and Stories of the Wild Woman Archetype''''' is a book by [[Jungian analyst]], author and poet [[Clarissa Pinkola Estés]], Ph.D, published in 1992 by [[Ballantine Books]]. It spent 145 weeks on [[The New York Times Best Seller list]] over a three-year span, a record at the time.<ref name="Mendoza221">Sylvia Mendoza, ''The Book of Latina Women: 150 Vidas of Passion, Strength, and Success'', Adams Media, 2004, p. 221.</ref>. Estés won a Las Primeras Award from the [[Mexican American]] Women's Foundation for being the First Latina on the ''[[New York Times]]'' Best Seller list.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Legacy of Latina Leadership: Las Primeras Awardees, 1990-2014 |publisher=[[MANA, A National Latina Organization]] |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/2799c9_91617dd6a32a46f88d769ffadd86ab17.pdf}}</ref> The book also appeared on other best seller lists, including ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', and ''[[Library Journal]]''.
Estés had been producing popular audiotapes of her stories and research and was approached by publishers to turn them into a book.<ref name="Mendoza221"/>
In ''Women Who Run with the Wolves'', Estés analyses [[myths]], [[fairy tales]], [[Folklore|folk tales]] and stories from different cultures to uncover the Wild Woman archetype of the feminine psyche. The book stems from these interpretations of old tales and creates this wolf-woman parallel, by incorporating her own previous studies that suggest "wolves and women are relational by nature."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/28/weekinreview/conversations-clarissa-pinkola-estes-message-for-all-women-run-free-wild-like.html|title=Conversations/Clarissa Pinkola Estes; A Message for All Women: Run Free and Wild Like the Wolf|last=Johnson|first=Dirk|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en}}</ref> The notion of the archetype is associated with the work of [[Carl Jung]]. Estés produces this new collection of words to describe the female psyche in ''Women who Run with the Wolves'' as it is a psychology of women in the truest sense, a knowing of the soul. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.clarissapinkolaestes.com/women_who_run_with_the_wolves__myths_and_stories_of_the_wild_woman_archetype_101250.htm|title=Women Who Run With the Wolves: Myths and Stories of the Wild Woman Archetype - Dr. Clarissa Pinkola Estés|website=www.clarissapinkolaestes.com|access-date=2018-10-26}}</ref>
